abstract: Christina Iverson makes her New York Times Crossword debut.
snippet: Christina Iverson makes her New York Times Crossword debut.
lead_paragraph: TUESDAY PUZZLE — Becoming a new parent to a baby is a miracle, a life-changing event full of joy, wonder, intense bonding and lack of sleep. Watching your bundle of joy grow and take on the world around them is amazing. We can all agree on that much, right?

abstract: Joe Biden is in the hot seat.
snippet: Joe Biden is in the hot seat.
lead_paragraph: It’s crunchtime for the Democratic presidential candidates. The second set of debates will air live from Detroit on Tuesday and Wednesday — with 20 contenders split evenly between the two nights — and the four-hour spectacle is being pitched as an elimination round worthy of “The Bachelorette.” The debates scheduled for September and October have a higher threshold for participation in terms of poll numbers and campaign donations, which means that, among the more marginal candidates, those who fail to distinguish themselves in this showdown might not get another shot.

abstract: Some Democrats are proposing a government alternative to private insurance. But allowing people to choose such a plan may destabilize the A.C.A., some experts say.
snippet: Some Democrats are proposing a government alternative to private insurance. But allowing people to choose such a plan may destabilize the A.C.A., some experts say.
lead_paragraph: It seems a simple enough proposition: Give people the choice to buy into Medicare, the popular federal insurance program for those over 65.

abstract: For half of the candidates, it may be their last chance to make an impression on the national debate stage.
snippet: For half of the candidates, it may be their last chance to make an impression on the national debate stage.
lead_paragraph: When 20 Democratic presidential candidates gather for the second round of debates this Tuesday and Wednesday, about half of them will do so with the understanding that it will probably be their last time debating on the national stage this election cycle.

headline_main: DealBook Briefing: Don’t Bet on the Trade War Ending Quickly

abstract: Ms. Harris is forging her own path on the health care issue, putting forth a plan for providing Medicare for all Americans that stops short of the complete overhaul Bernie Sanders has proposed.
snippet: Ms. Harris is forging her own path on the health care issue, putting forth a plan for providing Medicare for all Americans that stops short of the complete overhaul Bernie Sanders has proposed.
lead_paragraph: Senator Kamala Harris of California, who is increasingly seeking to carve out an ideological lane separate from the most progressive Democrats running for president, laid out a new plan Monday for providing Medicare for all Americans, with a twist that stops short of the complete overhaul of the health insurance system that Senator Bernie Sanders of Vermont has proposed.

abstract: Elizabeth Warren and Pete Buttigieg are among the presidential candidates earning approval from the government-reform group End Citizens United.
snippet: Elizabeth Warren and Pete Buttigieg are among the presidential candidates earning approval from the government-reform group End Citizens United.
lead_paragraph: Seven Democratic presidential candidates, including Senator Elizabeth Warren of Massachusetts and Mayor Pete Buttigieg of South Bend, Ind., have promised that their first legislation as president would be an ambitious clean-government bill, earning their campaigns an influential reform group’s stamp of approval.
